","Gonadarche","Pubarche","Thelarche"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThelarche\u003C/strong\u003E refers specifically to the onset of breast development, typically the first visible sign of female puberty. It results from rising oestrogen levels and usually occurs between ages 8-13 years.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPuberty\u003C/strong\u003E refers to the entire process of sexual maturation, not specifically breast development. \u003Cstrong\u003EAdrenarche\u003C/strong\u003E refers to maturation of the adrenal glands and rising androgens. \u003Cstrong\u003EGonadarche\u003C/strong\u003E refers to the activation of the gonads and rising sex hormones in response to pituitary gonadotropins. \u003Cstrong\u003EPubarche\u003C/strong\u003E refers to the appearance of pubic hair.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Thelarche refers to the onset of breast development, typically occurring as the first visible sign of female puberty.","Thelarche usually occurs between ages 8-13 years in females, triggered by rising oestrogen levels."],"references":["Javed A, Lteif A. Development of the human breast. Semin Plast Surg. 2013 Feb;27(1):5-12. doi: 10.1055/s-0033-1343989. PMID: 24872732; PMCID: PMC3706056.","Burlo F, Lorenzon B, Tamaro G, Fabretto A, Buonomo F, Peinkhofer M, Vidonis V, Vittori G, Faleschini E, Barbi E, Tornese G. Prevalence and characteristics of thelarche variant. Front Endocrinol (Lausanne). 2023 Dec 1;14:1303989. doi: 10.3389/fendo.2023.1303989. PMID: 38107513; PMCID: PMC10722224.","U\u00e7ar A, Saka N, Ba\u015f F, Bundak R, G\u00fcn\u00f6z H, Darendeliler F. Is premature thelarche in the first two years of life transient? J Clin Res Pediatr Endocrinol. 2012 Sep;4(3):140-5. doi: 10.4274/Jcrpe.709. PMID: 22985613; PMCID: PMC3459162."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97399"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16265"}